---

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @Butternut Squash{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @Shallot{1%unit}(thinly sliced). Peel and mince or grate @Garlic{1%clove}(minced). Remove and discard any large stems from @Kale{4%ounce}; chop into bite-size pieces.

Toss butternut squash on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{drizzle}, @Salt{} and @Pepper{}. Roast on top rack, tossing halfway through, until browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, melt @Butter{1%TBSP} in a large pan over medium heat. Add @Panko Breadcrumbs{¼%cup}, salt, and pepper. Toast, stirring, until golden, ~{2-3%minutes}. Transfer to a small #bowl{} and set aside. Turn off heat; wipe out pan.

Once water is boiling, add @Cavatappi Pasta{6%ounce} and cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Reserve 1 cup pasta cooking water, then drain.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for panko over medium-high heat. Add @Italian Chicken Sausage Mix{9%ounce} and season with salt and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{}. Wash out pan.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for panko over medium-high heat. Add shallot and a pinch of salt; cook, stirring, until slightly softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in garlic and cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Reduce heat under pan to medium. Stir in kale and a splash of water; cook, stirring and adding more splashes of water as needed, until kale is tender and water has evaporated, ~{5-7%minutes}.

> Use pan used for turkey or sausage here.

Add @Cream Sauce Base{4%ounce}, @Veggie Stock Concentrate{1%unit}, and ¼ cup reserved pasta cooking water to pan with kale. Cook, stirring, until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Remove pan from heat; stir in @Sour Cream{1.5%tablespoon}, @Parmesan Cheese{3%tablespoon}, and @Butter{2%TBSP} until melted and combined. Season with salt and pepper.

Stir drained cavatappi and squash into pan with sauce until thoroughly coated.

> TIP: If sauce is too thick, add more pasta cooking water and a drizzle of olive oil.

Divide pasta between plates and top with toasted panko. Serve.

> Stir turkey or sausage into sauce along with drained cavatappi.

> Poultry is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.